I just finished the first law trilogy a week or so ago, I thought it was solid. I didn’t draw that comparison myself. 
As for name of the wind, it took me like 2 months to get past chapter 3 but once I was trough that I cruised through both books. I love that you called him the comic book guy lol that’s apt. 
Brandon Sanderson reigns supreme in my mind though.
If nothing else, I certainly appreciate how quickly Sanderson writes
His stories are typically enjoyable, he does a good job world building, but there always seems to be one character in each of his books that I find insufferable that I’m supposed to like
When it’s the main character...*sad trombone*

His magic systems are well thought out and typically explained from an outside perspective. The worlds are fantastic and believable, to the degree that a fantastical world can be. 
It’s a shame you’re annoyed by characters. I haven’t run into that. Which ones irk you the most?

Vin is the main culprit. She was basically the same as every other YA post apocalyptic character that came out at that time. Found her to be super cookie cutter and annoying. That’s probably just me though
How did we get from talking about how quality Malazan was, totally dropping that, and discussing bad fantasy?
Anyway, to answer the "how good is it on a scale of 1-10 question" asked way up the thread, let me tell you a story.
Have you read our conversation history in any of these channels before? Seems super par for the course.
It's 2013, it's the summer, I'm deployed to Africa with nothing to do.
Months go by.
I'm no longer deployed to Africa, I return to my home in Germany.
I check my credit card bill.
There's a BS $9.99 charge from Amazon, on the 26th of each month I was deployed.
So I call Amazon.
After some initial outrage, the lady pulls up the actual "recurring" charges I'm discussing with her, and starts reading the names of them off to me.
I had been so into Malazan that I had finished each book on the exact timeline of a month, despite also having a job and taking three online classes for the entire length of my deployment.
I couldn't stop those bitches.
Thank you for your time and consideration of my gripping tale.
There's legit moments in those books where I had to stop and put the book down to get my shit together emotionally.
I couldn’t get into those books. I keep trying every so often.
I couldn’t either. I had no reason to care about the characters.
As much as I enjoy them, I do definitely recognize that they're not for everyone.
The writing is very prose oriented, and Steven Erikson's writing style basically makes the reader have to feel like a detective to really keep track of what's going on.

That said, if you actually got to the end of Gardens of the Moon and weren't so invested in Kruppe and his whole gang that you went into conniptions when you found out the second book wasn't about them....
Then I would be fairly amazed.
